            specifies whether TLS is allowed for XDQP.</span>
        </admin:help>
      </xs:appinfo>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:simpleType name="ssl-certificate-template-id">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>
        The id of the certificate template in the security database.
      </xs:documentation>
      <xs:appinfo>
        <admin:default>0</admin:default>
      </xs:appinfo>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:restriction base="xs:unsignedLong">
    </xs:restriction>
  </xs:simpleType>

  <xs:element name="ssl-certificate-template" type="ssl-certificate-template-id">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>
        The certificate template. When
        a certificate template is specified, the App Server uses an SSL
        encrypted protocol (e.g. https, davs, xccs). The certificate
        template specifies the common information for the individual SSL
        certificates needed for each host in the group. <p>You can add a new
        certificate template by navigating to
          <a href="/add-certificate-template.xqy">Security &gt; Certificate Templates &gt; Create</a></p>
      </xs:documentation>
      <xs:appinfo>
        <admin:default>0</admin:default>
        <admin:select>certificate-template</admin:select>
        <admin:optional>true</admin:optional>
        <admin:help xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          <span class="help-text">
            <span style="color:#800000">ssl certificate template</span>
            specifies the certificate template for the App Server. When
            a certificate template is specified, the App Server uses an SSL
            encrypted protocol (e.g. https, davs, xccs). The certificate
            template specifies the common information for the individual SSL
            certificates needed for each host in the group.
          </span>
        </admin:help>
      </xs:appinfo>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:simpleType name="ssl-hostname">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>
        A hostname.
      </xs:documentation>
      <xs:appinfo>
      </xs:appinfo>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:restriction base="xs:token">
      <xs:minLength value="0"/>
      <xs:maxLength value="64"/> <!-- per RFC 2459 -->
    </xs:restriction>
  </xs:simpleType>

  <xs:element name="ssl-hostname" type="ssl-hostname">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>
        The host name for the server's SSL certificate. This is
        useful when many servers are running behind a load balancer. If not
        specified, each host will use a certificate specifying its own hostname.
        Note that per RFC 2459, hostnames must not exceed 64 characters in length.
      </xs:documentation>
      <xs:appinfo>
        <admin:default>""</admin:default>
        <admin:optional>true</admin:optional>
        <admin:help xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
        <span class="help-text"><span style="color:#800000">ssl hostname</span>
        specifies the hostname for the server's SSL certificate. This is
        useful when many servers are running behind a load balancer. If not
        specified, each host will use a certificate for its own hostname.</span>
        </admin:help>
      </xs:appinfo>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

